<subSubSection id="C3786525FFDEFFA6FF78FF2E6A592E16" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDD36AEFFDEFFA6FF78FF2E6A592E16" blockId="34.[151,1436,151,861]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDEFFA6FF78FF2E6A072FC2" bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
BL 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FEAAFF2E6AAF2FC2" box="[325,441,151,176]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="3.725" valueMax="3.95" valueMin="3.5">3.50–3.95</number>
. General body color brownish; coxae, trochanters, and base of femora yellowish brown, remaining of legs brown. Pronotum with anterior lobe lighter, with or without a pair of lateral pruinose areas. Forewing dark brown, with a basal white macula starting from humeral angle and passing posterior margin of pronotum; at apex another rounded white macula (
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDEFFA6FD3BFEBD68302E6E" box="[724,806,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1910,1932]" captionTargetBox="[304,1279,638,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[304,1283,637,1889]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 18. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia recens, (B) P. rotundanotata, (C) P. splendoris (macropterous), (D) P. splendoris (micropterous)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285799/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FCE5FEBD68302E6E" box="[778,806,260,284]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Male hind femur with a row of small teeth on inner margin through almost entire length. Male hind tibia clavate. Paramere with a basal dorsal notch, tapering towards apex (
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDEFFA6FF34FEF56A382E16" box="[219,302,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,582,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[198,1389,577,1957]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Lateral view of genital capsule of male, (A) P. nieseri, (B) P. platensis, paramere in posterior view, (C) P. recens, (D) P. rotundanotata, (E) P. spinifera, (F) P. splendoris, (G) P. williamsi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285801/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FEE0FEF56A382E16" box="[271,302,332,356]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3786525FFDEFFA6FF28FED669A82DDA" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDD36AEFFDEFFA6FF28FED669A82DDA" blockId="34.[151,1436,151,861]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDEFFA6FF28FED66A5A2EFA" bold="true" box="[199,332,367,392]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Discussion.</emphasis>
Despite being exclusive from the interior of bromeliads, this species has a wide geographical range, from 
<collectingCountry id="F375763EFFDEFFA6FEC9FE2D6A852EDF" box="[294,403,404,429]" name="Honduras" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Honduras</collectingCountry>
to southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F375763EFFDEFFA6FDBCFE2D698D2EDF" box="[595,667,404,429]" name="Brazil" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. It also shows a wide morphological variation among populations, which has leaded some researchers to identify it differently. Most of the specimens herein mentioned display shape of forewings maculae similar to those illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF34B5FFFDEFFA6FD14FE656F4A2E86" author="Polhemus" box="[763,1116,476,501]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Polhemus, D. A. (1991) A review of the veliid fauna of bromeliads, with a key and description of a new species (Heteroptera: Veliidae). Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 99 (2), 204 - 216." type="journal article" year="1991">
Polhemus &amp; Polhemus (
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FBF8FE656F452E86" box="[1047,1107,476,500]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1991.0">1991</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. However, some specimens show white pruinosity on anterior lobe of pronotum, besides an oval-shaped apical macula on forewing. 
<taxonomicName id="4C624D2DFFDEFFA6FAC2FDB96A0E2D4E" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manausana">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDEFFA6FAC2FDB96A0E2D4E" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Paravelia manausana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDEFFA6FEC5FD9D6A682D4E" box="[298,382,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[302,1288,208,1449]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[296,1291,195,1453]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 17. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia foveata, (B) P. lanemeloi (paratype), (C) P. manausana, (D) P. nieseri (holotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285798/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FE8DFD9D6A682D4E" box="[354,382,548,572]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
C) is a similar species, from which 
<taxonomicName id="4C624D2DFFDEFFA6FCCEFD9C68912D4E" box="[801,903,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="recens">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDEFFA6FCCEFD9C68912D4E" box="[801,903,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. recens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the brownish color, rounded apical macula of forewings, and tapering paramere (
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDEFFA6FD75FDFE69F92D12" box="[666,751,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,582,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[198,1389,577,1957]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Lateral view of genital capsule of male, (A) P. nieseri, (B) P. platensis, paramere in posterior view, (C) P. recens, (D) P. rotundanotata, (E) P. spinifera, (F) P. splendoris, (G) P. williamsi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285801/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDEFFA6FD3FFDF169F92D12" box="[720,751,584,608]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
C), whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C624D2DFFDEFFA6FC76FDF06F202D12" box="[921,1078,585,608]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manausana">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDEFFA6FC76FDF06F202D12" box="[921,1078,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">P. manausana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the coloration is dark brown to black, the apical macula is suboval and almost reaches the posterior margin of wing, and the paramere does not taper towards apex, which is subtruncate distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
